<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="396">Etymology Presumably from Gr chalkos, copper, alluding to the body color.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="396">
Diagnosis A small-medium species, with angulate postpetiole and bicolorous head in the major. Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181857" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole chalcoides Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole chalcoides Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalcoides">chalcoides</taxonomicName>
, but distinguished in the major by the smooth humerus, which is less prominent in dorsal-oblique view; broader, angular-sided postpetiolar node; and yellow occiput; and in the minor by the unarmed humerus and smooth pronotal dorsum. Also similar but less so to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33595" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arhuaca">arhuaca</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole caulicola Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole caulicola Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caulicola">caulicola</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181903" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole mincana Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole mincana Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mincana">mincana</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33982" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole sagana Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sagana Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sagana">sagana</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181939" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole schmalzi Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole schmalzi Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmalzi">schmalzi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34062" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tragica Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tragica Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tragica">tragica</taxonomicName>
, differing in details of body shape, and sculpture as illustrated, and color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="396">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.04, HL 1.24, SL 0.54, EL 0.14, PW 0.52. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.52, HL 0.60, SL 0.50, EL 0.12, PW 0.38.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="396">color Major: anterior third of head and occiput yellow, remainder of head brown; body yellowish to light brown;</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="396">appendages light yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="396">Minor: brownish yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="396">Range Hidalgo and Veracruz, Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="396">biology Mann (in Wheeler 1914c) found numerous small colonies in oak-pine woodland near Molino Guerrero, an ore mill on the eastern slope of the mountain range east of Pachuca; they were nesting under stones. I found a nest of several chambers about 15 cm below the surface in the dense clay soil of Liquidambar woods adjacent to a meadow at approximately 1700 m on the south slope of Pico Orizaba. Workers were foraging along an adjacent trail. Sexual pupae were in the nest on 23 August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
